<div id="review_3029009063" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3029009063" />
    <a title="Laura | What&#39;s Hot?" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5898609-laura-what-s-hot"><img alt="Laura | What&#39;s Hot?" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1546301832p2/5898609.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3029009063?book_show_action=true">Oct 29, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Laura | What&#39;s Hot?" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Laura | What&#39;s Hot?" href="/user/show/5898609-laura-what-s-hot">Laura | What&#39;s Hot?</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/41021698-the-liar">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3029009063" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12720699932904144544">~ 2.5-3 stars ~ <br/><br/>I was excited to get stuck into Stephen Fry’s debut novel to see if it lived up to his reputation but to be honest I’m still rather unsure about the whole thing. Simultaneously witty and pretentious, clever and confusing, I went through some passages where I really didn’t get what the *point* was, but maybe, after all, that was the point?<br/><br/>I can totally see why this book has garnered both love and hate and my gut feeling is that it will be loved by those who are more familiar with </span>
  <span id="freeText12720699932904144544" style="display:none">~ 2.5-3 stars ~ <br /><br />I was excited to get stuck into Stephen Fry’s debut novel to see if it lived up to his reputation but to be honest I’m still rather unsure about the whole thing. Simultaneously witty and pretentious, clever and confusing, I went through some passages where I really didn’t get what the *point* was, but maybe, after all, that was the point?<br /><br />I can totally see why this book has garnered both love and hate and my gut feeling is that it will be loved by those who are more familiar with world of public schools, Cambridge University and elite circles. The Liar satirises these worlds through the character Adrian Healy, a compulsive liar, but whilst some passages had me sniggering, others had me rolling my eyes at just how pretentious it was. <br /><br />All in all, I wouldn’t be in a hurry to recommend this to my friends though it did serve its purpose as quick-paced and light entertainment on my dreary commute to work. I’m keen to pick up some more of Fry’s fiction writing to see how they compare as I feel like this debut novel did altogether demonstrate just how much potential the comedian has as an author. <br /><br />Find more book recommendations and book content on <a href="https://whatshotblog.com" rel="nofollow noopener">whatshotblog.com</a> and <a href="https://instagram.com/whatshotblog" rel="nofollow noopener">@whatshotblog</a>.</span>
  <a data-text-id="12720699932904144544" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


